    <h1>Why Strapless?</h1>
    <p>Strapless isn't a CSS micro/mini/nano-framework. It's a CSS boilerplate. It just makes your plain HTML look good.</p>
    <p>With only six semantic CSS classes to worry about (action, reaction, success, failure, info, warning), Strapless frees you from the overprescriptive cruft of frameworks. Use the grid you like. Snag a dropdown menu that works for your project, not the one we picked and named for you. You were probably going to do that <em>anyway</em>, right?</p>
    <p>Strapless aims to let you work how you want, building your project from the ground up, instead of chiseling it out of a we-know-better block of marble.</p>
    <p>Basically, Strapless makes your HTML look like this page. Try it out now by changing the base color. Then, download that color's CSS file and use it to start building&mdash; from the ground up.</p>
</section>

<section id="philosophy" class="reaction">
    <h1>Philosophy</h1>
    <ul>
        <li>Full support for HTML elements (and only HTML elements)</li>
        <li>Smart CSS rules for good out-of-the-box layouts</li>
        <li>Wide support for base colors and patterns</li>
        <li>Opinionated but simple design rules</li>
        <li>Easy to overwrite when everything goes horribly wrong</li>
        <li>No grid, no columns, no components</li>
        <li>There are no ugly colors, only ugly color schemes</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section id="less">
    <h1>Less</h1>
    <p>Strapless offers some other handy Less files, like:</p>
    <dl>
        <dt>mixins.less</dt>
        <dd>Mixins for handling text color issues and other Lesser issues.</dd>

        <dt>variables.less</dt>
        <dd>A very short variable file that you will never have to scroll through.</dd>

        <dt>targets.less</dt>
        <dd>Simple, reusable target mixins for handling responsiveness.</dd>

        <dt>colors.less</dt>
        <dd>Powerful, flexible color scheme generation.</dd>

        <dt>patterns.less</dt>
        <dd>Simple SVG-based color-shifting patterns ready to drop in to your project.</dd>

        <dt>normalize.less</dt>
        <dd><a href="http://www.github.com/necolas/normalize.css">Includes a great normalize file</a> to make your HTML and CSS work easier.</dd>
    </dl>
    <h2>Useful Less variables</h2>
    <p>Strapless calculates some useful variables for your project:</p>
    <dl>
        <dt>@scheme-type</dt>
        <dd>Returns either <em>light</em>, <em>medium</em>, or <em>dark</em> depending on your base color.</dd>
        <dt>@success and @failure</dt>
        <dd>A well-paired successful green and failure red that work with your theme</dd>
        <dt>@info and @warning</dt>
        <dd>A calming blue and more urgent orange demarking information</dd>
        <dt>@action and @reaction</dt>
        <dd>A generic opposing pair of colors based on your project's @base-color</dd>
    </dl>
</section>

